 but the content of the sentence was intact. Based on this, it was guessed that the Broca's and Wernicke's areas solely have a hand in grammatical structure and comprehensibility, respectively. %0a%3c %0a%3c  After neuroimaging studies started though, these areas became more and more understood. The primary finding is that the Broca's and Wernicke's areas do not have such simple rules as previously believe (this also extends generally to the rest of the brain.. each brain region is involved in so many tasks and skills)! For example, the Broca's area (called in most neuroscience literature as the Inferior Frontal Gyrus, or IFG), is made up of three distinct sections (called Brodmann's areas 44, 45, and 47) have different functions, like roles in phonological processing, semantic processing, and syntax. %0a%3c %0a%3c For written language, other areas have been implicated, like the angular gyrus, the supramarginal gyrus, and the 'visual word form area'. The first two mentioned here deal mostly with turning the orthogonal form (the written words and their form) into the phonological information about that word. The visual word form area (VWFA) is an interesting and special case in the literature, particularly since reading has not been around long enough for our brains to evolve to read. So, how do we use this area to read anyways?%0a%3c %0a%3c Some have argued that the VWFA is a case of 'neural recycling' where we reuse preexisting skills and constraints set by the brain and apply them to a new task. So, it is likely the VWFA has some general pattern recognition principle, that when applied to reading, helps us recognize distinct word forms.%0a%3c %0a%3c I could discuss further the strange neuroscience of language, but it is quite a dense topic. Two takeaway points are that the brain is never as simple as it seems and that our brain is constantly using its resources to adapt to the new challenges the world presents.%0a%3c %0a%3c References (warning: these are kinda dense neuroscience articles but this is where I learned this information from):%0a%3c %0a%3c Dehaene, S. and Cohen, L. (2007).  Cultural Recycling of Cortical Maps. Neuron, 56, 384-398.%0a%3c %0a%3c Cohen, L., & Dehaene, S. (2004). Specialization within the ventral stream: The case for the visual word form area. NeuroImage, 22, 466-476.%0a%3c %0a%3c Bookheimer, S. (2002). Functional MRI of language: New approaches to understanding the cortical organization of semantic processing. Annual Review of Neuroscience, 25, 151-188.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: E:)%0a%3c (:Category: Varia:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
